      </sidebyside>

      <sidebyside>
        <image>
          <latex-image label="ASA2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations
              % Triangle PQR
              \coordinate (P) at (0,1);
              \coordinate (Q) at (3,4);
              \coordinate (R) at (7,1);

              \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

              \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
              {angle=R--P--Q};; 

              \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
              {angle=P--Q--R};; 
              \draw[black] (1.8,2.6)--(1.6,2.8);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        
        <image>
          <latex-image label="AAS2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations
              % Triangle PQR
              \coordinate (P) at (0,1);
              \coordinate (Q) at (3,4);
              \coordinate (R) at (7,1);

              \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

              \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
              {angle=R--P--Q};; 

              \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
              {angle=P--Q--R};;

              \draw[black] (3.5,0.8)--(3.5,1.2); 
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <image>
          <latex-image label="SAS2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

            % Triangle PQR
            \coordinate (P) at (-2,4);
            \coordinate (Q) at (4,4);
            \coordinate (R) at (0,1);

            \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

            \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
            {angle=R--P--Q};; 

            \draw[black] (0.5,3.8)--(0.5,4.2); 
            \draw[black] (0.6,3.8)--(0.6,4.2); 

            \draw[black] (-1.2,2.4)--(-0.8,2.6); 

            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p xml:id="auto_2juvdbms">
        Identify pairs of congruent triangles.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_0sfeljuv">
        From the pairs of congruent triangles you have identified, which pairs fit the following criteria:
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_cemexqmb">
        <ol xml:id="auto_8h0esurh">
          <li xml:id="auto_kevaathg">
            <p xml:id="auto_pavega3u">
              The three sides of one triangle is equal to the three sides of the corresponding triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_n4z1p667">
            <p xml:id="auto_sl8dvbhr">
              Two sides and an included angle of one triangle is equal to the two corresponding sides and the included angle of the other triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_zwt6n5d9">
            <p xml:id="auto_ijy8h25p">
              One side and two included angles of one triangle is equal to the corresponding side and the two included angles of the other triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_g1p4r40z">
            <p xml:id="auto_03k7qfv2">
              One side and the hypotenuse of a right-angled triangle are equal to the hypotenuse and the corresponding side of another right-angled triangle.
            </p>
          </li>  
        </ol>
      </p>    
    </statement>
  </activity>
      <exploration xml:id="auto_cbgjpm1n">
        <title>Determining Congruence</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_h47n08zv">
        Two triangles are congruent if one can be translated, rotated, and/or reflected to obtain the other. The following interactive demonstrates this fact.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-congruence-overlap">
        <caption>
            Try to get the blue and red triangles to overlap with the black triangle.
        </caption>

        <interactive xml:id="interactive-congruence-overlap" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/congruence-overlap.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-congruence-overlap" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
        </interactive>
    </figure>
            
    </exploration>

      <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_i4on41uf">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_gg7x06t8">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gdkj58gr">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_pkr9rtwq">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2j33gnyu">
                    To formalise the five congruence tests and address common misconceptions.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s051errs">
            <alert>Misconception:</alert> Knowing all three angles does NOT prove congruence <mdash/> triangles can have the same angles but different sizes.
        </p>
    </axiom>
  <insight xml:id="auto_wqb8kzfu">
    
      <p xml:id="auto_3sje6in5">
              Figure with the same size and shape are said to be <term>congruent.</term>   
       </p>
       <p xml:id="auto_0vjo2ang">
        The symbol for congruence is <m>\cong.</m>
       </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_htbwi6ax">
              Figures with the same shape but different size are said to be <term>similar.</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_q4y2vic1">
              Congruence can also be applied to line segments and angles. 
        </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_ejue80tr">
            Congruence in triangles depends on the measure of the sides and angles.
            Two triangles are said to be congruent if a pair of the corresponding sides and corresponding angles are equal.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_qaob32ar">
        Criteria for congruence tests in triangles include:
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_drc502hj">
        <ul xml:id="auto_3roei9b5">
          <li xml:id="auto_5vwflci3">
            <p xml:id="auto_y0q00aik">
             <term>Side-side-side (SSS):</term> the three sides of one triangle is equal to the three sides of the corresponding triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_sg11mgnl">
            <p xml:id="auto_hx2g1i7k">
              <term>Side-angle-side (SAS):</term> two sides and an included angle of one triangle is equal to the two corresponding sides and the included angle of the other triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_k63dmm4n">
            <p xml:id="auto_tx8lyvcr">
              <term>Angle-side-angle (ASA):</term> one side and two included angles of one triangle is equal to the corresponding side and the two included angles of the other triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_1fntr65v">
            <p xml:id="auto_r42bd7qo">
              <term>Right angle-hypotenuse-side (RHS):</term> one side and the hypotenuse of a right-angled triangle are equal to the hypotenuse and the corresponding side of another right-angled triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_f3a4iqhr">
            <p xml:id="auto_6bjfttl2">
              <term>Angle-angle-side (AAS):</term> one side and two included angles of one triangle is equal to the corresponding side and the two included angles of the other triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <table xml:id="auto_fhirv94i">
        <title>Summary of Congruence Tests</title>
        <tabular halign="left">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Test</cell>
                <cell>What You Need</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>SSS</cell>
                <cell>Three pairs of equal sides</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>SAS</cell>
                <cell>Two pairs of equal sides + included angle</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>ASA</cell>
                <cell>Two pairs of equal angles + included side</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>RHS</cell>
                <cell>Hypotenuse + one other side in right triangles</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>AAS</cell>
                <cell>Two pairs of equal angles + non-included side</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
        
  </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_oroa4j6v">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_cs4n0b80">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_eff4ypw8">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4lw93nlx">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_w7m6dnrq">
                    To apply congruence tests to determine whether pairs of triangles are congruent, including coordinate geometry.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_k6g741x0">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_d56so91g">
                    The teacher guides learners through worked examples, emphasising correct identification of the congruence test and proper vertex correspondence in congruence statements.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_z1bj3nal">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_zzxizoxs">
          Check if the triangles below are congruent and state the test of congruence criterion.
        </p>

        <image>
        <latex-image label="side_angle_side_exercise1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}

          \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

          % Triangle ABC
          \coordinate (A) at (-6,4);
          \coordinate (B) at (-8,1);
          \coordinate (C) at (-2,1);

          \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
          \node[above] at (A) {A};
          \node[left] at (B) {B};
          \node[below right] at (C) {C};

          \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$60^\circ$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
          {angle=C--B--A};; 

          % Triangle PQR
          \coordinate (P) at (-2,4);
          \coordinate (Q) at (4,4);
          \coordinate (R) at (0,1);

          \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
          \node[above] at (P) {P};
          \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
          \node[below right] at (R) {R};

          \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$60^\circ$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
          {angle=R--P--Q};; 

          \draw node at(-7,3) {$3\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (-5.4,.7) {$8\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (0.5,4.2) {$8\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (-1.2,2.4) {$3\, cm$}; 
                    
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
     </statement>
     <solution>
      <p xml:id="auto_q1i9o0pb">
          From the figure above, we have: 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bt211lrd">
          <ol marker="(i)">
            <li xml:id="auto_p5k8g88a">
              <p xml:id="auto_wz42dvq0">
                 Corresponding sides
              </p>
              <p xml:id="auto_ry862s1s">
                 Sides <m>AB = PR = 3\, cm \text{ and } BC = PQ = 8\,cm</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_qblda3ky">
              <p xml:id="auto_yhq67lss">
                 Corresponding angles.
              </p>
              <p xml:id="auto_sougo3q9">
                 <m>\angle B = \angle P = 60^\circ.</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p> 
        <p xml:id="auto_vzmkc2up">
          Therefore, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR</m> by <term>SAS</term> criterion
        </p>
     </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_sss1">
      <statement>
         <p xml:id="auto_m3jph9fx">
           A surveyor needs to determine whether two triangular plots of land are equal in shape and size.
            She measures the sides of the first plot and finds them to be <m>15</m> m, <m>20</m> m, and <m>25</m> m. 
            The second plot has sides measuring <m>15</m> m, <m>20</m> m, and <m>25</m> m. 
          </p>

        <image>
          <latex-image label="side_side_side_exercise1">
            \begin{tikzpicture}

            % Triangle DEF
            \coordinate (D) at (-6,4);
            \coordinate (E) at (-8,1);
            \coordinate (F) at (-3,1);

            \draw[thick] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;

            \node[above] at (D) {D};
            \node[left] at (E) {E};
            \node[below right] at (F) {F};

            \draw node at (-7,3) {$15\, cm$};
            \draw node at (-5.5,0.6) {$20\, cm$};
            \draw node at (-4.8,2.6) {$25\, cm$};


            % Triangle XYZ
            \coordinate (X) at (1,4);
            \coordinate (Y) at (5,4);
            \coordinate (Z) at (3,1);

            \draw[thick] (X) -- (Y) -- (Z) -- cycle;

            \node[above] at (X) {X};
            \node[above] at (Y) {Y};
            \node[below] at (Z) {Z};

            \draw node at (3,4.5) {$15\, cm$};
            \draw node at (4,2.6) {$20\, cm$};
            \draw node at (2,2.6) {$25\, cm$};

            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_i6pcwv7o">
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li xml:id="auto_ozh01mxn">
              <p xml:id="auto_aee32rd1">
                Are the two triangular plots congruent? Explain
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xoae7ym0">
              <p xml:id="auto_3q0r5e3n">
                State the congruence criterion used
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_vkxrxylz">
              <p xml:id="auto_e2n7cf71">
                 If one side of the second plot was <m>24</m> m instead of <m>25</m> m, would the triangles still be congruent? 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

    <solution>
      <p xml:id="auto_wny4sbx8">
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li xml:id="auto_0bj8vbks">
            <p xml:id="auto_226qgfhb">
              Yes, the two triangular plots are congruent because all three corresponding sides are equal
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_vb55pg4u">
            <p xml:id="auto_5mqbw9d8">
              The congruence criterion used is <term>SSS</term>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_rpkqylcw">
            <p xml:id="auto_9kitcgjn">
              No, the triangles would not be congruent because for SSS criterion, <strong>all three</strong> corresponding sides must be equal.
               Changing one side length would produce a different triangle.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7351gdit">
              
              <m>DE = XY = 15\, cm</m>
              <m>EF = YZ = 20\, cm</m>
              <m>DF = XZ = 25\, cm</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="auto_rhs1">
  <statement>
    <p xml:id="auto_zsauvf7s"> A ladder of length <m>5</m> m leans against a vertical wall, reaching a height of <m>4</m> m.
        Another ladder of the same length leans against a different wall, also reaching a height of <m>4</m> m.
        The base of each ladder is on horizontal ground. 
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_ow1hw8xr">
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="auto_zenbubu3">
          <p xml:id="auto_jk6ds8rb">
             Are the two triangles congruent
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_vjpmr1ra">
          <p xml:id="auto_wo0jl4hc">
            State the congruence criterion used.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_cxqsf2jn">
          <p xml:id="auto_18m1kaal">
            If the second ladder reached a height of 3.5 m instead of 4 m, would the triangles still be congruent?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <image>
      <latex-image label="right_angle_hypotenuse_side_exercise1">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes}

        % First ladder triangle ABC
        % A = top of ladder, B = foot on wall, C = ground point
        \coordinate (A) at (-6,5);
        \coordinate (B) at (-6,1);
        \coordinate (C) at (-3,1);

        % Draw wall and ground
        \draw[thick] (-7,1) -- (-2,1);   % ground
        \draw[thick] (-6,1) -- (-6,5);   % wall

        % Ladder
        \draw[thick] (A) -- (C);

        % Right angle INSIDE
        \draw 
          pic["$90^\circ$", draw=orange, angle radius=0.5cm, angle eccentricity=1.3]
          {angle=C--B--A};

        % Labels
        \node[left] at (A) {A};
        \node[left] at (B) {B};
        \node[below] at (C) {C};

        % Side labels
        \node[left] at (-6,3) {$4\,m$};
        \node[below] at (-4.5,1) {$3\,m$};
        \node[above right] at (-4.5,3.2) {$5\,m$};


        % Second ladder triangle DEF
        \coordinate (D) at (3,5);
        \coordinate (E) at (3,1);
        \coordinate (F) at (6,1);

        % Draw wall and ground
        \draw[thick] (2,1) -- (7,1);   % ground
        \draw[thick] (3,1) -- (3,5);   % wall

        % Ladder
        \draw[thick] (D) -- (F);

         % Right angle INSIDE
        \draw 
          pic["$90^\circ$", draw=orange, angle radius=0.5cm, angle eccentricity=1.3]
          {angle=F--E--D};
        % Labels
        \node[left] at (D) {D};
        \node[left] at (E) {E};
        \node[below] at (F) {F};

        % Side labels
        \node[left] at (3,3) {$4\,m$};
        \node[below] at (4.5,1) {$3\,m$};
        \node[above right] at (4.5,3.2) {$5\,m$};

        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
      </statement>

      <solution>
      <p xml:id="auto_w3urjz8n">
        From the diagram and the given information:
      </p>

      <p xml:id="auto_x79o92wt">
        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li xml:id="auto_ps1jq2fe">
            <p xml:id="auto_eg3rtcnq">
              Each ladder forms a right-angled triangle with the wall and the ground.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wcunivzc">
              <m>\angle B = \angle E = 90^\circ</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="auto_nnlmffon">
            <p xml:id="auto_twjkxra0">
              The hypotenuse (ladder length) in both triangles is equal.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t22c4ejd">
              <m>AC = DF = 5</m> m
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="auto_0r6cb6dg">
            <p xml:id="auto_x79c0iru">
              One corresponding side (height reached on the wall) is equal.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_huxzge4t">
              <m>AB = DE = 4</m> m
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p xml:id="auto_1kpwm69x">
        Therefore, the two triangles are congruent by the 
        <term>RHS</term> (Right angle-Hypotenuse-Side) criterion.
      </p>

      <p xml:id="auto_q45zhsld">
        If the second ladder reached a height of <m>3.5</m> m instead of <m>4</m> m, 
        then the corresponding sides would no longer be equal. 
        Since one of the required equal sides would differ, 
        the triangles would not be congruent.
      </p>

      </solution>
</example>
    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-Extended-activity">
      <title>Extended activity</title>
      <p xml:id="auto_qi413b1z">
        <term>Work in groups</term>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_fzcgc9ib">
        Trace and cut out the following shapes on a piece of paper.
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="shapes_1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
             % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-9,-6) grid (9,6);
              
            \fill[purple,opacity=0.3](-7,5) -- (-7,3) -- (-5,3) -- cycle;
            \draw[purple,thick] (-7,5) -- (-7,3) -- (-5,3) -- cycle;
            \node[purple] at (-6,3.5) {$A$};

            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3](-4,5) -- (-2,5) -- (-2,3) -- (-4,3) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-4,5) -- (-2,5) -- (-2,3) -- (-4,3) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-3,4) {$B$};

            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3](-1,5) -- (2,5) -- (2,3) -- (-1,3) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-1,5) -- (2,5) -- (2,3) -- (-1,3)-- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-.5,4) {$C$};

            \fill[red,opacity=0.3](3,5) -- (6,5) -- (3,3) -- cycle;
            \draw[red,thick] (3,5) -- (6,5) -- (3,3) -- cycle;
            \node[red] at (3.5,4.5) {$D$};

            \fill[orange,opacity=0.3](-7,2) -- (-5,2) -- (-4,0) -- (-8,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[orange,thick] (-7,2) -- (-5,2) -- (-4,0) -- (-8,0) -- cycle;
            \node[orange] at (-6.5,1) {$E$};

            \fill[yellow,opacity=0.3](-3,2) -- (-1,2) -- (-1,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[yellow,thick] (-3,2) -- (-1,2) -- (-1,0) -- cycle;
            \node[yellow] at (-1.5,1.5) {$F$};

            \fill[green,opacity=0.3](1,2) -- (3,2) -- (1,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[green,thick] (1,2) -- (3,2) -- (1,0) -- cycle;
            \node[green] at (1.5,1.5) {$G$};

            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3](4,2) -- (7,2) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (4,2) -- (7,2) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (5,1.5) {$H$};

            \fill[red,opacity=0.3](-8,-1) -- (-6,-1) -- (-6,-3) -- (-8,-3) -- cycle;
            \draw[red,thick] (-8,-1) -- (-6,-1) -- (-6,-3) -- (-8,-3) -- cycle;
            \node[red] at (-7,-2) {$I$};

            \fill[orange,opacity=0.3](-5,-1) -- (-5,-3) -- (-2,-3) -- cycle;
            \draw[orange,thick] (-5,-1) -- (-5,-3) -- (-2,-3) -- cycle;
            \node[orange] at (-4,-2.5) {$J$};

            \fill[orange,opacity=0.3](-1,-1) -- (2,-1) -- (2,-3) -- (-1,-3) -- cycle;
            \draw[orange,thick] (-1,-1) -- (2,-1) -- (2,-3) -- (-1,-3) -- cycle;
            \node[orange] at (.5,-2) {$K$};

            \fill[orange,opacity=0.3](3,-1) -- (7,-1) -- (6,-3) -- (4,-3) -- cycle;
            \draw[orange,thick] (3,-1) -- (7,-1) -- (6,-3) -- (4,-3) -- cycle;
            \node[orange] at (5,-2) {$L$};


          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_dmlnvh4n">
        1. Identify figures that are directly congruent.
      </p>
      
        <p xml:id="auto_b668hiqg">
          Example: <m>B \cong I.</m> <m>B</m> fits directly on <m>I</m> without flipping, thus <m>B \text{ and } I</m>
                are said to be <term>directly congruent.</term> 
      </p>
      
      <p xml:id="auto_tadoks8e">
        2. Identify figures that have opposite congruence.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_bdk9okdr">
        Example: <m>E \text{ and } L</m> do  not fit directly but when you flip <term>(lateral inversion)</term> figure <m>L</m> and fit it on <m>E,</m> they align. 
        This is called <term>opposite congruence.</term>  
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_2a347puq">
        3. Identify:
        <ul xml:id="auto_0a8u3fki">
          <li xml:id="auto_ovc1309t">
            <p xml:id="auto_hoek1x02">
               The figures with the same shape.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_vy81jlk3">
            <p xml:id="auto_tjya0c1v">
              The figures with the same size.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_bm8546et">
            <p xml:id="auto_6819ob8p">
              The figure with same size and shape.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>  
      </p>
